Yes, that's what I mean. Here's a thorough explanation:
Consider evaluating e.g.

   "xample of a sample. EOS This is another example of a sample. EOS And here is yet another example of a sam"
   (NB: intended clipping, this is what happens in the validator right now.)

and scoring the loss on that, versus evaluating, as three separate samples:

   "This is an example of a sample. EOS"
   "This is another example of a sample. EOS"
   "And here is yet another example of a sample. EOS"
   (NB: this is NOT happening in the validator right now.)

Then you will reward a model that knows what to predict *after* EOS, which is a bit silly. Also the start of the evaluated sample is mid-sentence, which is a bit silly to try to predict as well. And as this is how it is evaluated, it is also how it is most probably trained. The token after EOS, i.e. the first token of a sample, is highly predictable (only ~160 tokens in the top 50%) so not training on the "after EOS" token would be costly.
However, in practice, the "after EOS" token has no value as EOS signals End Of Stream, which is *THE END OF THE GENERATED STREAM OF TOKENS*. Or I'm missing something, could be possible, I never actually use LLMs, I just try to train them.
Also there is the more subtle issue that in "sample EOS sample EOS sample" etc there could even be cross sample correlations as the samples are taken in possibly correlated batches.
How bad is this? I don't know. But the capacity of the model is limited, by definition, and some of that capacity is now spent on something useless, so it is nonzero bad.
And while I'm on it... same holds for the tokenizer which is apparently very good in code snippets that never occur in the dataset, just look at the vocab and see the tokens starting with TAB, or containing any permutation of "()[]+", for example. So even more capacity is wasted on embed_weights and lm_head on non-existent tokens. I asked before, but I still don't know any reason to enforce a tokenizer.

I think it might work out fine if we would take the sum of token losses of each sample. So the evaluation should calculate the total loss of complete sample as retrieved from the dataset, and not the average loss of a (fixed) number of tokens. Looking at the the vocab we can come up with some examples, to see what would happen. For instance, the vocab now has tokens “President” and “president” where my new tokenizer would only have “P”, “p”, and “resident”, all else equal. My tokenizer and model would have two loss values versus one loss value in the original model for the word “[Pp]resident”. Now suppose scoring a sample reading “Trump was the 45th president of the USA”, still with all else equal. I predict that the sum of losses will be identical between models: my model will predict 50%/50% “P”/“p” + 100% “resident”, and the original model will predict 50%/50% “President”/“president”. All fine I think. No need to complicate matters with bytes/token. My tokenizer is 1 token smaller (assuming I needed to add "resident") and I may try to use the 2*4096 params I just saved to increase the model in any other dimension. 
The question then is what can be trained better: a bigger or a smaller tokenizer, with a trade-off in remaining model parameters, sample throughput (bigger tokens means more samples/PETAFLOPS), required GPU memory, etc. Also interesting: how to find an efficient vocab, how much time to spend on that before training, starting from scratch or taking an existing model and changing the vocab… It would be really interesting to see what happens.
The tokenizer can also be frozen at some future point, to become the tokenizer of the top model, e.g. when switching to a different model size. This competition would produce something meaningful: an efficient tokenizer that fits a well known dataset, plus a ton of variants that didn't win but are still publicly available.

## Announcement 📢 (1/2)

Dear Subnet-9 community, the big update you were all waiting for is here!

Macrocosmos and Taoverse are excited to announce the schedules for new competitions and their respective details and reward distributions.

In addition to the competitions we previously presented in our roadmap, we are going to announce the launch of an experiment in the coming days, we will call it, 7B-star or 7B* . This experiment is an effort to better understand the dynamics of changing the timestamp epsilon. It will be presented as a sub-competition of the 7B competition, all miners participating in 7B will be automatically evaluated on 7B* , which will have the same constraints but a low epsilon value of 0.001. By setting epsilon to such a low value, we wish to prove/refute the hypothesis that a lower epsilon would produce a better model, and prevent competition stagnation. If it does, then we will update all our competitions to use that low value. If it doesn’t, then we prove that any strategy for lowering epsilon, including decay,  would add no value to the subnet.

- The 700M model competition will be launched.

One quick thing I found reading your miner code: you might not be ignoring pad tokens correctly.

1. You are using padded-row training approach. This means the input ids have pad tokens in it.
2. You are using GPT2LMHeadModel for calculating the loss, by passing both input_ids and labels into the forward. This creates nn.CrossEntropyLoss within the forward, with default params.
3. nn.CrossEntropyLoss ignores -100 from labels by default, but you did not substitute pad tokens with -100 in the labels. So probably the loss also accounts for predicting padding tokens.
4. Also, GPT2LMHeadModel shifts the logits and labels within the forwards, but you are shifting them before passing them, resulting in shifting twice!

labels = input_ids.clone()
labels = torch.where(labels == tokenizer.pad_token_id, -100, labels)

I also see some problems with the validator: it picks a new set of pages (default: 1 page = 100 samples) to evaluate the models on each iteration, and compares the median loss on that new set to the best loss *on a different set*. If these sets are small, and small is relative here (these sets have to be pretty big), this comparison is meaningless. It's almost more like searching for a set of pages on which a model happens to score well, rather than finding a model which scores well in general. You can make this more clear by computing the median loss on a single page of 100 samples, doing that many times and look at the statistics.

If I evaluate a model, I do it on a predefined benchmark set of ~20.5k samples, which is guaranteed not to overlap with the training set (this is best of course, but fineweb is huge so it's not likely that random samples will overlap a lot with the benchmark set). It allows me to see improvements of order 0.01% (which allows to determine if you're training in the right direction even).

You cannot compare the average token loss across different tokenizers, so the 1.6 is very different from the 2.1 the current top-model provides (using Xenova/gpt-4, vocab size 100263). The average sample length (in tokens) will be quite a bit longer using gpt2 (vocab size 50257). We (in SN29) believe it's perfectly fair to compare total sample loss  (summed token loss), and you can check our leaderboard for this metric between our two different competitions.

However that set needs to change to stope miners from over fitting

Right. To compare models on a single summary statistic (e.g. average token loss), you need to evaluate them on the same (VERY LARGE) sample set. A small set will never do.
However, it is still true that different models can be good at different things and both be valuable. In that case, you would want to merge the models to get the best of both worlds. (If training starts from a common ancestor, and two models are trained on different sample sets, they will each only improve on samples that have some "overlap" with their respective training sets).

Let me stress one more time: this set has to be large to make a meaningful statement about one model being better than another based on the average loss. The reason is that the estimate of the average based on a finite set of samples has a finite error bar (which is *not* the standard deviation of the sample loss distribution). The best method to determine it, is to assume some distribution of the sample losses, e.g. normally distributed, and then fit the average and standard deviation. This will result in somewhat meaningful estimates of the error bars on both.
The strategy of model comparison based on individual sample-scoring (like the SN9/SN29/old SN6 validators do) is much more straight-forward, but of course also requires a somewhat large set.

## Announcing Release v4.5.0 📢
https://github.com/macrocosm-os/pretraining/tree/v4.5.0

We have released version 4.5.0 with the following changes:

**1. Sample Packing is Back.** Block `4_001_017`
Unpacking samples makes sense, especially for validation—no contexts are mixed, reducing the risk of contamination. However, we have two reasons to believe that sample packing should still be used:

-Validating on unpacked samples encourages training on unpacked samples, which is not the standard pretraining method used for popular architectures. By reverting to sample packing, we aim to encourage miners to adhere to a standard, well-tested pretraining method. That being said, we are conducting experiments to quantify the pros and cons of both methods, and will be communicating the results soon. But for now, we will proceed with the well-known packing method.

-The median sequence length in our validation datasets is significantly smaller than the maximum sequence length allowed for our competitions. This opens the possibility of optimizing models for specific sequence lengths, which is dataset-specific and not in line with our goal of building more general models.

**2. Faster Epsilon Decay:** Block `4_001_017`
Epsilon will now decay from 0.005 to 0.0001 (instead of 0.001) to allow smaller improvements.

**3. More Robust Miner Ranking:** `Immediate effect`
The pairwise win rate between two models is now binary—a miner either wins or loses against another miner. This prevents models with multiple copies from having an advantage. While model copying has been used by some miners, it has not significantly affected miner ranking in our experiments with the current epsilon interval. However, this improvement will be more useful with lower epsilon values.

## Short Article  🗞️ 

**Pushing the Limits of Subnet-9: Smarter Dataset Mixing**

Determining the pretraining data mix is a fundamental design parameter that has not received the attention it deserves. At Subnet 9, we are set to change that. But before diving deeper into the subject, let's take a step back and review some of the key design factors that contribute to making a pretrained LLM a better one.

**Stepping into the Designer's Shoes**

Most LLM development strategies can be broadly qualified as either model-centric or data-centric. For a long time, the focus of the AI community was primarily on the former. Researchers sought inspiration from the brain, its neocortex and the neural dynamics behind learning and knowledge accumulation. The perceptron, Boltzmann machines, feature descriptors, convolutional and pooling layers, and even the very concept of attention emerged from this line of research. Model-centric design decisions often involve architectural components, model size, and training strategies.
Relating this to Subnet 9, factors such as model architectures and number of parameters, tokenizers and  training strategies can all be considered as model-centric choices. At Subnet 9, we provide miners with varying degrees of freedom in deciding these factors.
.

** Determining the Data Cocktail**

As soon as model-centric approaches, particularly with ConvNets and Transformers, demonstrated their effectiveness, researchers realized that careful selection of the training datasets—including their composition, scale, and quality—is just as important, if not more so, than architectural choices. Data has always been a fundamental part of the process, but its true significance was often underestimated.

At Subnet 9, we believe it is time to place data at the core of incentive design. Until now, we have relied on Refined Web and Fine Web datasets, which are based on Web data curation without much control over the data mix.  In contrast, state-of-the-art models often take a different approach to collecting pretraining data. Here are some examples:
Meta reported using a carefully chosen data mix to optimize Llama 3 models' performance. Web  data was classified into domains such as general knowledge, math, code, and multilingual, with the final mix set at 50%, 25%, 17%, and 8%, respectively.
The proportion of each data domain was determined through experimentation. Various mixes were tested on smaller-scale models, and the optimal combination was chosen for scaling up. 

Qwen2 models were also pretrained following a similar approach, though the exact data mix was not disclosed in their technical report. 

You can check their technical reports here:
LLama3: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2407.21783
Qwen2: https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.10671
.

📢 **The Announcement: Subnet-9 to the cocktail party**

In next week's release, Subnet-9 will take the first step towards making controlled data mixing a core design choice in model pretraining. We will roll out a new 14B competition, identical to the existing one but with a different mix of data domains. All 14B miners will be automatically evaluated in this new competition, with the winner determined based on WTA. The goal is to determine the data mix that brings models closer to state-of-the-art, and to assess its importance as a design choice.

To really squeeze the most out of this experiment, we will boost our dashboard with live performance monitoring to track miners' progress across each data domain as well as on SOTA benchmarks--the go-to standard for comparing pretrained models.

**Finally...**

We believe that this is an important step in building a more mature pretraining ecosystem in Bittensor: Putting data at the heart of our design choices, and building SOTA-centric benchmarking and monitoring tools.
